Stocks edged lower in morning trading on Wall Street Wednesday as technology companies slipped and weighed down major indexes again.The S&P 500 fell 0.1% as of 10:17 a.m. Eastern. The tech-heavy Nasdaq fell 0.6%. The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 33 points, or 0.1%, to 36,832 and pulled just above the record high it set a day earlier.Roughly 60% of stocks in the benchmark S&P 500 made gains, but technology companies, because of their huge size, have a lot of sway in moving the index. Tech companies led gains on Monday, but then pulled the broader market lower on Tuesday.Microsoft fell 2% and software maker Adobe shed 3.8%.U.S. crude oil prices rose 1.4% and drove solid gains for energy companies. Exxon Mobil rose 2.4%.A mix of financial and health care companies also made gains.ADVERTISEMENTBond yields were relatively stable. The yield on the 10-year Treasury edged lower to 1.65% from 1.66%.Coronavirus pandemicCOVID case counts may be losing importance amid omicronIn Israel, omicron drives records, zigzag policy, 4th shots
